As a result, Co0.6Ir0.4/TiO2 has the best performance with 100% conversion for HB dehydrogenation relative to Co/TiO2, Ir/TiO2, TiO2, and Co0.6Ir0.4 catalyst at 323 K (Fig. 3
                     a). 6 equivalents of gas (H2+N2) per HB (1 mmol) are released within 0.53 min, and the corresponding turnover frequency (TOF) with 5625 h−1 is higher than the reported most catalysts applied to HB dehydrogenation (Table 1
                     ) [29,30,32,34–41,51,58–63]. Additionally, without TiO2 substrate, the reaction time of Co0.6Ir0.4 is 8.53 min, with conversion and TOF of 96.5% and 342 h−1, respectively. Moreover, with catalysts of Co/TiO2 and Ir/TiO2, the reaction cannot complete and only 3.86 (64.3% conversion) and 3 (50.0% conversion) equivalents of gas can produce in 2.53 and 3.10 min for Co/TiO2 and Ir/TiO2, respectively. Although Co/TiO2 and Ir/TiO2 have poor catalytic performance for the HB decomposition reaction, the bimetallic catalyst Co0.6Ir0.4/TiO2 has excellent catalytic performance for this reaction, which can be attributed to the synergistic effect of the bimetals. By the way, pure TiO2 shows no activity (Fig. 3a) and supported Co or Ir can hardly complete the HB dehydrogenation reaction. But it starts changing when added a small amount of Ir, such as 10%, to form CoIr alloy (Fig. 3b). The catalytic activity increases with the increase of Ir, until its content is up to 40%. The activity does not get any better when further increases the amount of Ir (Fig. 3b), indicating that the optimal ratio of Co: Ir is 0.6:0.4 in CoIr/TiO2 and the interaction between Co and Ir is non-negligible. Moreover, when the total mole of metal is 0.05 mmol, the Co0.6Ir0.4/TiO2 catalyst can reach the TOF maximum of 6923 h−1 at 323 K (Fig. S6). The samples of Co combined with other noble metals are also tested, and all of them show the worse performance (Fig. S7).
